<subSubSection pageId="6" pageNumber="7" type="reference_group">
<paragraph blockId="6.[264,750,433,459]" box="[264,750,433,459]" pageId="6" pageNumber="7">
<taxonomicName authority="McAlpine, 1960" authorityName="McAlpine" authorityYear="1960" box="[264,750,433,459]" class="Insecta" family="Lonchaeidae" genus="Lonchaea" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="7" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="haplosetifera">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[264,550,433,459]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="7">Lonchaea haplosetifera</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="McAlpine" box="[557,750,433,459]" lastPageId="6" lastPageNumber="23" pageId="6" pageNumber="22" refString="McAlpine, J. F. (1960) Chapter XVI. Diptera (Brachycera): Lonchaeidae. In Hanstrom, B., Brink, P. &amp; Rudebeck, G. (Eds.). South African animal life. Results of the Lund University Expedition 1950 - 1951. Volume 7. Almqvist and Wisell, Goteborg, Stockholm, Upsalla, pp. 327 - 376." type="book chapter" year="1960">
McAlpine, 
<number box="[691,750,433,459]" pageId="6" pageNumber="7" value="1960.0">1960</number>
</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="6.[264,1324,497,1603]" pageId="6" pageNumber="7">
<bibRefCitation author="McAlpine" box="[264,468,497,523]" lastPageId="6" lastPageNumber="23" pageId="6" pageNumber="22" refString="McAlpine, J. F. (1960) Chapter XVI. Diptera (Brachycera): Lonchaeidae. In Hanstrom, B., Brink, P. &amp; Rudebeck, G. (Eds.). South African animal life. Results of the Lund University Expedition 1950 - 1951. Volume 7. Almqvist and Wisell, Goteborg, Stockholm, Upsalla, pp. 327 - 376." type="book chapter" year="1960">
McAlpine (
<number box="[399,460,497,523]" pageId="6" pageNumber="7" value="1960.0">1960</number>
)
</bibRefCitation>
described this species from a series of females. They were characterised in his key by having a combination of a single katepisternal bristle, basal tarsomeres yellow and dark squamal fringes. In addition the lateral margin of scutellum has eight or ten fine setulae in multiserial rows between the usual scutellar bristles. The male described here also exhibits this combination of characters and is ascribed to this species.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="6" pageNumber="7" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="6.[264,1324,497,1603]" pageId="6" pageNumber="7">Description. Male: Head: Eyes with very short and sparse hairs. Frons with very short hairs, no hairs present on the orbital plate above the orbital bristle. Lunule orange Frons and face with slight silver pollinosity. Antennae with first flagellomere long, extending down past the mouth margin, black dorsally and apically with orange colouration ventrally, becoming almost entirely orange basally. Pedicel also orange. Arista microscopically pubescent..</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="6.[264,1324,497,1603]" pageId="6" pageNumber="7">
Thorax: Katepisternum with one single strong bristle with a single hair posterior to it. Scutellum on margin with multiserial rows of about 
<number box="[887,916,977,1003]" pageId="6" pageNumber="7" value="10.0">10</number>
hairs on each side between apical and lateral bristles, no hairs between apical bristles. Squamae with fringe dark and rather densely haired. Legs black, tarsomeres almost entirely yellow, only slightly darkened on apical segments.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="6.[264,1324,497,1603]" pageId="6" pageNumber="7">
Male genitalia: 
<figureCitation box="[512,577,1137,1163]" captionStart="FIGURE 2" captionStartId="7.[264,367,1538,1562]" captionTargetBox="[357,1234,290,1522]" captionTargetId="figure@7.[346,1241,288,1526]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="FIGURE 2. Male genitalia of: Lonchaea haplosetifera McAlpine. 1. epandrium and associated structures, lateral view. 2. aedeagus lateral view. Silba budongo sp. nov. 3. epandrium and associated structures, lateral view. 4. ventral view. 5. aedeagus lateral view." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/171272/files/figure.png" pageId="6" pageNumber="7">
Fig. 
<number box="[561,577,1137,1163]" pageId="6" pageNumber="7" value="2.0">2</number>
</figureCitation>
; 
<emphasis box="[597,633,1137,1162]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="7">
<number box="[597,633,1137,1162]" pageId="6" pageNumber="7" value="1.2">1,2</number>
</emphasis>
. Epandrium slightly wider than high with a marked anteroventral process. Cerci as high as the epandrium is deep with a long basal stalk and with club shaped apex,, with short hairs on the apical club. Surstyli extending posteriorly from the epandrium as a broad column with a concave apex, bearing hairs on the dorsal margin at the apex. Aedeagus relatively simple and U­shaped but with more ornate processes basally.
</paragraph>
